\description{
Test a chosen set of pairwise differences between the predicted means of a
fitted model, with multiplicity adjustment over the chosen set and optional
splitting into independent subgroups. Unlike \code{\link[=multiple_comparisons]{multiple_comparisons()}}, which
is means-centric and summarises \emph{all} pairwise comparisons via a compact
letter display, \code{pairwise_comparisons()} is difference-centric: it returns a
tidy table with one row per requested comparison (estimate, standard error,
statistic, degrees of freedom and adjusted p-value). This honestly represents
selective and irregular comparison sets, for which letter groupings are not
valid.
}
\details{
It works for every model supported by \code{\link[=multiple_comparisons]{multiple_comparisons()}}, because a
pairwise difference needs only the standard error of the difference (SED)
matrix that the prediction machinery already returns.
\subsection{Relationship to \code{multiple_comparisons()}}{

The two functions share the same predicted means and standard errors of
differences, so for a given \code{adjust} method they report the same comparisons.
Testing all pairs here (\code{pairs = NULL}) with a particular \code{adjust} yields the
same adjusted p-values as \code{\link[=multiple_comparisons]{multiple_comparisons()}} with the same \code{adjust} —
the difference is presentation (a tidy table of differences and a forest plot,
versus means, confidence intervals and letter groupings). The exception is
Tukey's HSD, which is exact only for the complete set of all pairwise
comparisons and so is the domain of \code{\link[=multiple_comparisons]{multiple_comparisons()}}; \code{adjust = "tukey"} is therefore not accepted here.
}

\subsection{\code{pairs} syntax and sign convention}{

The estimate for a pair is \code{mean(level1) - mean(level2)}, in the order
written (\code{"A-B"} gives A − B). The \code{level1} and \code{level2} columns make the sign
unambiguous. With \code{:} joining interaction cells and \code{-} separating the two
sides of a pair, the string form is unambiguous only when no factor level
contains a \code{-}; a level containing \code{-} referenced via the string form is an
error directing you to the list form. Reversed or duplicated pairs
(\code{"A-B"} and \code{"B-A"}) are de-duplicated with a warning, since duplicates would
inflate the adjustment family.

For an interaction \code{classify}, the \code{:}-joined components of each level label
must be in the same order as \code{classify} (e.g. \code{"A:X"} for
\code{classify = "Trt:Site"}, not \code{"X:A"}); the same applies to the level names
used in \code{contrasts}. A label that names no existing cell is rejected with the
list of available levels, but a mis-ordered label that happens to name
another valid cell is used silently — so when the factors share level names,
check the component order matches \code{classify}.
}

\subsection{\code{by} semantics}{

\code{by} must be a subset of the \code{classify} factors. Within each group, pair
labels reference the remaining (non-\code{by}) factor levels. For example,
\code{classify = "Trt:Site"}, \code{by = "Site"}, \code{pairs = "A-B"} compares Trt levels A
and B within each Site. A group with fewer than two levels is skipped with a
warning. In an unbalanced design a requested comparison may reference a level
that is absent from some groups: such a comparison is skipped (with a warning)
in the groups where it cannot be computed and reported in those where it can.
A level that is absent from \emph{every} group — or that was aliased — is instead
an error, since that indicates a mistake rather than an incomplete design.
}

\subsection{Standard error and degrees of freedom for \code{contrasts}}{

For a general contrast the standard error and degrees of freedom depend on
the model engine:
\itemize{
\item For models predicted via \code{emmeans} (\code{aov}, \code{lm}, \code{\link[nlme:lme]{nlme::lme()}},
\code{\link[lme4:lmer]{lme4::lmer()}}, and \code{aov} with \code{Error()} strata) the estimate, standard
error and degrees of freedom are obtained directly from
\code{\link[emmeans:contrast]{emmeans::contrast()}} on the model's reference grid. The degrees of freedom
are therefore the \emph{exact} contrast df for that engine (Satterthwaite or
Kenward-Roger for mixed models, containment for \code{aov}/\code{Error()}), including
for contrasts spanning more than two levels — these cannot be recovered
from the SED matrix alone.
\item For \code{asreml} models the contrast variance is computed from the prediction
error covariance (reconstructed from the SED matrix), and the degrees of
freedom are the term's denominator df from \code{asreml::wald(denDF = "default")}
(a single Kenward-Roger-style value shared by all contrasts within the
term, as ASReml-R does not provide a per-contrast approximate df).
}
}

\subsection{Transformations}{

Comparisons are reported on the model scale. A difference of transformed means
does not back-transform to a difference on the original scale (for log/logit
it is a ratio), so back-transformation is not attempted; a warning is issued
if the response appears to be transformed in the model formula.
}

\subsection{Confidence intervals}{

The per-comparison confidence intervals are \emph{not} simultaneity-adjusted: as
with the confidence-interval/letter note in \code{\link[=multiple_comparisons]{multiple_comparisons()}}, an
interval may exclude zero while the adjusted p-value is \verb{>= sig}. When this
happens a one-time \code{message()} notes it (suppressible with
\code{\link[=suppressMessages]{suppressMessages()}}).
}
}
\section{Supported model types}{

The comparison functions (\code{\link[=multiple_comparisons]{multiple_comparisons()}}, \code{\link[=pairwise_comparisons]{pairwise_comparisons()}}
and \code{\link[=reference_comparisons]{reference_comparisons()}}) work with any model for which a
\code{get_predictions()} method is defined. These are currently:\tabular{lll}{
   Model class \tab Fitted by \tab Notes \cr
   \code{aov}, \code{lm} \tab \code{\link[stats:aov]{stats::aov()}}, \code{\link[stats:lm]{stats::lm()}} \tab Fixed-effects linear models. \cr
   \code{aovlist} \tab \code{\link[stats:aov]{stats::aov()}} with an \code{Error()} term \tab Multi-stratum aov; gives comparison-specific (matrix) degrees of freedom. \cr
   \code{lme} \tab \code{\link[nlme:lme]{nlme::lme()}} \tab Linear mixed model. \cr
   \code{lmerMod} \tab \code{\link[lme4:lmer]{lme4::lmer()}} \tab Linear mixed model. \cr
   \code{lmerModLmerTest} \tab \code{\link[lmerTest:lmer]{lmerTest::lmer()}} \tab As \code{lmerMod}, with Satterthwaite degrees of freedom. \cr
   \code{asreml} \tab ASReml-R \code{asreml()} \tab Linear mixed model (commercial; not on CRAN). \cr
   \code{afex_aov} \tab afex \code{aov_car()} / \code{aov_ez()} / \code{aov_4()} \tab Factorial / repeated-measures ANOVA; gives comparison-specific (matrix) degrees of freedom. \cr
   \code{glmmTMB} \tab glmmTMB \code{glmmTMB()} \tab Generalized linear mixed model. Predictions are on the link scale with asymptotic (infinite) degrees of freedom; supply \code{trans} to back-transform. \cr
   \code{mmes} \tab sommer \code{mmes()} \tab Linear mixed model, via sommer's native \code{predict()}. SED from the prediction covariance; asymptotic (infinite) degrees of freedom (sommer provides none). \cr
}


ARTool (\code{art}) models are supported by \code{\link[=resplot]{resplot()}} but \strong{not} by the comparison
functions: the aligned rank transform makes mean-based comparisons inappropriate.
Use \code{ARTool::art.con()} for contrasts on ART models instead.

sommer \code{mmer} models (the legacy interface) are supported by \code{\link[=resplot]{resplot()}} but
\strong{not} by the comparison functions: current sommer provides no \code{predict()} method
for \code{mmer}. Refit with \code{sommer::mmes()} to use the comparison functions.

To add a new engine, write a \verb{get_predictions.<class>()} method returning a
list with elements \code{predictions}, \code{sed}, \code{df}, \code{ylab} and \code{aliased_names}
(plus \code{emmeans_grid} for engines backed by \code{\link[emmeans:emmeans]{emmeans::emmeans()}}), and add a
row to the table above.
}

\examples{

# Forest plot of pairwise differences (significant comparisons marked with *)
dat.aov <- aov(Petal.Width ~ Species, data = iris)
pc <- pairwise_comparisons(dat.aov, classify = "Species")
autoplot(pc)
dat.aov <- aov(Petal.Width ~ Species, data = iris)

# All pairwise comparisons (Holm-adjusted by default)
pairwise_comparisons(dat.aov, classify = "Species")

# A selected subset
pairwise_comparisons(
    dat.aov,
    classify = "Species",
    pairs = c("setosa-versicolor", "setosa-virginica")
)

# A general (non-pairwise) contrast: setosa vs the average of the others
pairwise_comparisons(
    dat.aov,
    classify = "Species",
    contrasts = list(
        "setosa vs rest" = c(setosa = 1, versicolor = -0.5, virginica = -0.5)
    )
)

# `by`: the same comparisons, adjusted independently within each group. Here a
# 2 x 3 factorial - compare tension levels within each wool type. The `pairs`
# labels reference the remaining (tension) factor.
m_wb <- aov(breaks ~ wool * tension, data = warpbreaks)
pairwise_comparisons(
    m_wb,
    classify = "wool:tension",
    by = "wool",
    pairs = c("L-M", "L-H")
)
}
\seealso{
\code{\link[=multiple_comparisons]{multiple_comparisons()}} for means-and-letters output. For guidance
on choosing between the two and on multiplicity adjustments, see
\code{vignette("choosing-multiple-comparisons", "biometryassist")}.
}
